# VerifyIndia — .cursorrules

## Project Overview
You are building VerifyIndia: a B2B supplier verification platform that connects Western buyers (Canada/US) with verified Gujarat, India manufacturers. Every supplier on this platform has been physically audited before appearing in search results.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 16 App Router (TypeScript only — no JavaScript files ever)
- Tailwind CSS v4 + custom components in src/components/
- Supabase: PostgreSQL database + Auth + Storage + Row Level Security (@supabase/ssr — NOT auth-helpers-nextjs)
- Stripe v21: supplier subscriptions (Bronze/Silver/Gold) + one-time buyer audit payments
- Resend: all transactional emails
- Google Gemini API: AI image generation for supplier photos and banners
- Vercel: deployment and hosting

## Architecture Rules — ALWAYS follow these

### Server vs Client Components
- Default to Server Components for everything
- Add "use client" ONLY when you need: useState, useEffect, event handlers, browser APIs
- Data fetching always happens in Server Components using the Supabase server client
- Never fetch data in Client Components unless it's user-triggered (form submit, button click)

### Supabase Usage
- Server Components and API routes: import from @/lib/supabase/server
- Client Components: import from @/lib/supabase/client
- NEVER use the service role key in any client-side code
- ALWAYS check auth before any database write operation
- ALWAYS use parameterized queries (Supabase does this — never concatenate raw SQL)

### API Routes
Every single API route must follow this exact pattern:
```typescript
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server'
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server'
import { z } from 'zod'

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  try {
    // 1. Auth check
    const supabase = await createClient()
    const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser()
    if (!user) return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 })

    // 2. Input validation
    const body = await request.json()
    const schema = z.object({ field: z.string().min(1) })
    const parsed = schema.safeParse(body)
    if (!parsed.success) return NextResponse.json({ error: parsed.error.flatten() }, { status: 400 })

    // 3. Business logic
    const { data, error } = await supabase.from('table').insert(parsed.data).select().single()
    if (error) throw error

    // 4. Success response
    return NextResponse.json({ data }, { status: 201 })

  } catch (error) {
    console.error('[API_ROUTE_NAME]', error)
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Internal server error' }, { status: 500 })
  }
}
```

### Forms
- ALL forms use react-hook-form + zodResolver
- NEVER use uncontrolled inputs with FormData
- NEVER use HTML form action attribute
- Validate on client AND server (same Zod schema reused for both)

### TypeScript
- No `any` types ever — use `unknown` and narrow it
- Define explicit return types on all functions
- Use the types from @/types/database.ts for all DB records
- Prefer interfaces over type aliases for object shapes

### File Naming
- Pages: app/route/page.tsx
- Layouts: app/route/layout.tsx
- API routes: app/api/feature/route.ts
- Components: components/category/ComponentName.tsx (PascalCase)
- Utilities: lib/name.ts (camelCase)
- Types: types/name.ts

### Styling
- Tailwind only — no inline styles, no CSS modules, no styled-components
- Use cn() from @/lib/utils for conditional classes
- Mobile-first responsive design (sm: md: lg: prefixes)
- Color system: gold (#C9A84C), ink (#0D0D0D), paper (#FAF8F3), trust (#1A4D3E)
- Never hardcode hex values in components — use Tailwind theme tokens

### Images
- Always use next/image, never <img>
- Always provide width and height
- Use priority prop on above-fold images only
- Supplier photos stored in Supabase Storage, accessed via public URL

### Error Handling
- Every async operation needs try/catch
- Show toast notifications for user-facing errors
- Log errors with console.error('[CONTEXT]', error) — include context in brackets
- Never show raw error messages to users

### Loading States
- Use React Suspense with fallback skeleton components
- Loading skeletons match the layout of the real content
- Never show a spinner alone — always skeleton that matches the shape

### Performance
- Fetch data as close to where it's used as possible
- Use Next.js cache() for repeated identical fetches in the same request
- Images: use appropriate sizes prop, never load desktop-size images on mobile

## Database Tables Reference
- profiles: id, user_id, role ('buyer'|'supplier'|'admin'), full_name, avatar_url, email
- suppliers: id, user_id, slug, name, city, state, industry, verification_score, verified_at, tier (bronze/silver/gold), status, min_order_value, export_capability, product_categories[], stripe_customer_id, active_until
- supplier_media: id, supplier_id, type (photo/video/certificate/document), url, caption, sort_order
- certifications: id, supplier_id, type, issuer, expiry_date, doc_url, verified
- audits: id, supplier_id, auditor_name, score, checklist (JSONB), report_url, audit_date
- buyers: id, user_id, company, country, industry, verified_email
- inquiries: id, buyer_id, supplier_id, message, status (pending/accepted/declined), estimated_order_value
- reviews: id, buyer_id, supplier_id, rating, title, text, order_value, verified_purchase
- subscriptions: id, supplier_id, plan, stripe_subscription_id, status, current_period_end

## Current Verification Tiers
- bronze: score 60-74, basic audit, 1 audit/year, ₹8,000/yr
- silver: score 75-89, full audit, 2 audits/year, ₹20,000/yr
- gold: score 90-100, premium audit, 4 audits/year, ₹45,000/yr

## Business Logic Rules
- Only suppliers with status = 'verified' appear in public search
- Buyers must be logged in to send inquiries
- One review per buyer per supplier (enforced by DB unique constraint)
- Stripe webhooks update tier and active_until in suppliers table
- File uploads: only jpg/png/webp/pdf, max 10MB, UUID filenames

## Frequent Mistakes to Avoid
| Wrong | Right |
|---|---|
| `import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js'` | `import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server'` |
| `<img src={url}>` | `<Image src={url} width={} height={} alt={} />` |
| `style={{ color: 'red' }}` | `className="text-red-500"` |
| `fetch('/api/...')` in Server Component | Use Supabase directly in Server Component |
| `import { stripe } from '@/lib/stripe'` | `import { getStripe } from '@/lib/stripe'` |
| `const { data } = supabase.from(...)` | Always await: `const { data } = await supabase.from(...)` |
| Hardcoding supplier IDs | Always use slugs in URLs, IDs internally |
| Using `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs` | This project uses `@supabase/ssr` only |

## When asked to build something, always:
1. Create the file with full TypeScript types
2. Handle loading states with Suspense/skeleton
3. Handle error states gracefully
4. Make it fully responsive (mobile-first)
5. Add SEO metadata if it's a page (generateMetadata)
6. Follow all the rules above without being reminded
